Title: Prologue — The Forest Road
Source: V4
Act: Prologue

===

~ Years before the story begins. Silas is revealed in action. Fleur is found. The question of why is left unanswered.

A forest road at dusk. A line of the Alderman's soldiers moves through it — not marching, hunting. They carry the tools of the purge: iron brands, binding chains, and the questions that come before both. They are looking for signs of the fire-touched. They are also looking for the Chosen One — and they test for it the way they test for everything: roughly, imprecisely, with the confidence of people who believe they will know it when they see it.

They stop a family on the road. The testing is crude. The family resists. The soldiers have little patience for resistance.

In a cottage set back from the road, Silas hears what is happening before she sees it. She takes the Book of Demons from its chest — not opening it, just taking it — and moves toward the sound.

What follows shows the audience who Silas was: fast, controlled, economical. She moves like someone who trained for years in close proximity to things that could kill her. The soldiers recognise her methodology before they fall. One gets a word out — Order — with something between accusation and recognition.

But she is not what she was. When the odds turn, she opens the Book. One page. A single breath of borrowed fire. It works — and the cost registers in her face immediately: not pain but the pull of it, and beneath the pull, something frightened. She shuts the Book before she wants to.

She turns. The family is dead. A small girl crouches in the road — unhurt, silent, watching Silas with an attention that does not belong to a child her age. This is Fleur.

Silas looks at her for a long moment. Something shifts when she sees the child. She picks her up. She takes her home.

The story does not say what Silas saw in that moment — whether it was guilt, or recognition, or the shape of the prophecy she helped write looking back at her from a small face in the dark. The question sits in the prologue like an ember. It will not be answered here.
